---
import ProjectLayout from "../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro";
import PhotoGallery from "../../components/PhotoGallery.jsx";
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="OERC Research — Maritime Autonomy"
  subtitle="Ocean Engineering Research Center · Supervised by Dr. Wei Qiu · Jan – May 2026"
  logo="/logos/mun-engineering.png"
  logoAlt="MUN Engineering"
  logoClass="bg-white/10 p-1"
  context="Work"
  tags={["C++", "OpenGL", "NURBS", "IGES", "Arduino", "Raspberry Pi", "LiDAR", "PID Control", "KiCad", "OpenCV", "MATLAB", "Research"]}
>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-4">Overview</h2>
    <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
      Three projects under Dr. Wei Qiu at Memorial's Ocean Engineering Research Center,
      all tied to maritime autonomy: a C++/OpenGL tool for hull geometry visualization,
      a research report on autonomous vessel communications for IMO/Transport Canada frameworks,
      and AEGIS, a scale-model autonomous SAR vessel I designed and built from scratch.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-6">Projects</h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">

      <!-- AEGIS -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-1">AEGIS — Autonomous SAR Vessel</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">Arduino · Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W · LiDAR · MLX90640 · OpenCV · KiCad</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-5">
          <p>
            AEGIS (Autonomous Environmental Guardian for Intelligent Search-and-Rescue) is a
            scale-model demonstrator targeting <span class="text-white/70">IMO Level 2/3 autonomy</span>.
            It is both a proof-of-concept and a proposed solution for a real operational gap:
            Canada has the longest coastline in the world, Arctic conditions make crewed patrols
            dangerous and expensive, and existing SAR fleets can't cover it all. AEGIS is designed
            to act as a forward-deployed search drone, arriving at the scene ahead of Coast Guard
            crews through continuous <span class="text-white/70">thermal patrol</span> to detect
            people in the water and monitor conditions in real time. The project ties directly back
            to my <a href="#mass-report" class="text-white/70 underline underline-offset-2 decoration-white/20 hover:decoration-white/40">MASS connectivity research</a>,
            which mapped out the communication and autonomy frameworks that informed how AEGIS
            handles sensor fusion, decision-making, and connectivity failover.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Platform & propulsion</h4>
          <p>
            The vessel started as my ONAE 6055 course project. The propulsion system runs on an
            <span class="text-white/70">Arduino Uno</span> with an <span class="text-white/70">L298N
            dual H-bridge</span> driving a brushed DC motor, a rudder servo for steering, and
            <span class="text-white/70">LiDAR sensors</span> feeding a <span class="text-white/70">PID
            control loop</span> for wall tracking and obstacle avoidance. For the Fueling the Future
            Fest poster competition I reframed the project as AEGIS and added a
            <span class="text-white/70">solar-powered independent sensor bus</span> (5V solar panel,
            <span class="text-white/70">TP4056</span> charge controller, 18650 Li-ion cell,
            <span class="text-white/70">MT3608</span> boost converter) that powers the entire SAR
            payload independently from the main propulsion LiPo. This separation means sensor
            systems stay online even if the drive battery is depleted.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Dual-processor architecture</h4>
          <p>
            The system runs a split architecture over <span class="text-white/70">UART serial</span>.
            The Uno owns all real-time motor <span class="text-white/70">PID</span> and rudder control,
            keeping latency-critical code on proven hardware. A <span class="text-white/70">Raspberry Pi
            Zero 2 W</span> handles everything compute-heavy: the thermal imaging pipeline,
            camera-based obstacle detection through <span class="text-white/70">OpenCV</span>,
            <span class="text-white/70">GPS/IMU</span> logging, WiFi streaming to a ground station,
            and 3D thermal map generation.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Thermal scanning & detection</h4>
          <p>
            The primary SAR sensor is an <span class="text-white/70">MLX90640 32×24 thermal array</span>
            mounted on a servo. It performs a 4-position sweep using the sensor's 110° wide-angle FOV
            for full 360° coverage. Each sweep produces a georeferenced thermal frame tagged with
            <span class="text-white/70">GPS coordinates</span> and <span class="text-white/70">IMU
            orientation</span>, logged to SD and optionally streamed live. These frames are composited
            into a real-time <span class="text-white/70">3D thermal point cloud</span> of the vessel's
            surroundings, where human heat signatures (~30°C+) are clearly distinguishable against
            cold open water. When the system detects a warm cluster above threshold, it triggers
            LEDs and a piezo buzzer to mark the detection location.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">Proposed: camera-based pathfinding</h4>
          <p class="text-white/40">
            If time and budget permit, the next sensor addition is a <span class="text-white/50">Pi
            Camera Module</span> on the CSI port for forward-looking visual obstacle detection via
            <span class="text-white/50">OpenCV</span>, complementing the LiDAR's range-based avoidance
            with image-based classification of obstacles and debris.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-xs font-mono text-white/30 uppercase tracking-wider pt-2">In progress: custom carrier PCB</h4>
          <p class="text-white/40">
            Currently designing a custom <span class="text-white/50">KiCad carrier PCB</span> that
            mounts under the Pi Zero 2 W as a HAT-style board. It consolidates
            <span class="text-white/50">power management</span>,
            <span class="text-white/50">I2C</span> sensor headers (MLX90640, GPS, IMU),
            servo output, UART crossover to the Uno, CSI passthrough, and status LEDs into one
            clean board, replacing the current breadboard wiring.
          </p>
        </div>
        <PhotoGallery
          client:only="react"
          images={[
            { src: "/projects/oerc/boat-thumb.png", alt: "Autonomous model vessel — side view", caption: "Side profile of the completed autonomous model vessel on its display stand" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/topfrontviewboat.jpg", alt: "Top-down view of vessel internals", caption: "Top-down view showing sensor mounts, wiring, and electronics layout" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/comp-1.jpg", alt: "AEGIS project poster and vessel display", caption: "AEGIS: Autonomous Environmental Guardian for Intelligent Search and Rescue — competition poster with vessel" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/comp-2.jpg", alt: "Team photo at competition", caption: "Team presenting the autonomous vessel at the engineering competition" },
            { src: "/projects/oerc/boatwork1.jpg", alt: "Workshop — prototyping and testing", caption: "Workshop session — prototyping and testing components" },
            { video: "/projects/oerc/boat-vid-1.mp4", alt: "Vessel testing video 1", caption: "Testing the autonomous vessel" },
            { video: "/projects/oerc/boat-vid-2.mp4", alt: "Vessel testing video 2", caption: "Tank testing — wall tracking and obstacle avoidance" },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <!-- Hull visualization tool -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-2">Ship hull visualization tool</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">C++ · OpenGL · NURBS · IGES</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            A C++/OpenGL desktop application that reads IGES hull geometry files and renders
            the NURBS surfaces, control nets, and surface normals in an interactive 3D viewer.
            You can rotate, zoom, toggle between wireframe/shaded views, and inspect individual
            surface patches.
          </p>
          <p>
            The tool plugs into Dr. Qiu's frequency-domain hydrodynamic solver, so it also
            ingests vessel mass-distribution data and displays computed motion RAOs, drift
            forces, and wave-induced loads alongside the geometry. Basically a preprocessing
            front-end for the solver that didn't have a visual interface before.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- MASS report -->
      <div id="mass-report" class="glass-card p-6">
        <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85 mb-2">MASS connectivity research</h3>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-white/25 mb-3">Technical writing · IMO standards · Transport Canada</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          A research report on communication requirements for Maritime Autonomous Surface Ships
          (MASS). The report maps connectivity needs across different operational phases and
          autonomy levels, aligned with current IMO and Transport Canada frameworks. This work
          directly informed the AEGIS design, particularly around how the vessel handles
          connectivity failover and what data it needs to stream vs. log locally.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>